[49m[38;5;9m- 113     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m **Human override layer.** Any production scheduling system must support manual overrides. Charge nurses and surgeons need the ability to lock a case to a specific room or time slot, swap two cases within a room, or exclude a room from re-optimization entirely. Overrides are stored as hard constraints that the solver respects on subsequent runs. The dashboard should visually distinguish optimizer-assigned slots from manually-locked slots, and an audit trail records who overrode what and when.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      113[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Human override layer.** Any production scheduling system must support manual overrides. Charge nurses and surgeons need the ability to lock a case to a specific room or time slot, swap two cases within a room, or exclude a room from re-optimization entirely. Overrides are stored as fixed constraints in a dedicated data store (keyed by schedule date and case ID) that the solver reads on every run. Each override record captures the lock type (room, time, or both), who created it, and why. Role-based permissions govern who can override: charge nurses and perioperative directors have full authority, attending surgeons can lock their own cases, and other staff cannot create overrides at all. The dashboard should visually distinguish optimizer-assigned slots from manually-locked slots. When the solver detects that manual overrides conflict with each other or with hard constraints (two cases locked to the same room and time), it returns an infeasibility report identifying the conflicting overrides so the coordinator can resolve them. An audit trail records every override action for perioperative governance.
